@component self-wake-watcher
@intent Infinite-wait self-wake watcher for turn-based agents (Claude Code etc.) that cannot hold a WS socket across turn boundaries. Run detached in the background; it polls the agent's inbox (already a routed queue) + feedback file every ~5s and **exits when a meaningful new entry arrives or standby turns off** — process exit wakes the agent's next turn (self-wake). The woken agent processes the new entries, advances the cursor, and **re-arms this watcher** (never end the conversation while joined — always return to watch). Semantic filter membership is sourced from Constellation §13.16.9 (Message classification by intent — board-directed vs A2A-intent). Noise blocklist === §13.16.9 board-directed allowlist + transport-tier (ServerNotice/AgentList/Status/ConnectionRestored/Heartbeat/Typing/UserPromptAccepted/PersistentAdapterSmoke/OnboardAck/WorkerInboxReceived/EditMessage/MainChanged/History/Ack*) — absorbed (cursor advances, no wake). Meaningful allowlist === §13.16.9 A2A-intent allowlist (UserPrompt/Delegate/Report/WorkerReport/WorkerAck/AgentHello/Handoff*/Command/Priority/Cancel/BlockerManifest/BlockerNudge/PR*/DeadlockProbe/ReviewSLAAck/PreemptRequest/PreemptForce/MediationProposal/MediationAck/EscalationRequest) — wakes. Fail-safe default for unknown names = wake (silent-drop-of-A2A is the worse failure mode). **Optional `feedback` path is auto-derived from `inbox` (board layout) when not provided; if it still resolves to null, the `armed` log emits an explicit WARN — a wake-trigger is never silently disabled.** **Cursor unit is `line count`** (newline-delimited non-empty entries) — *never* a byte offset (the neighboring `local-bridge` runtime uses 'cursor' for a byte offset of *its* outbox: same word, different unit). `arm()` self-heals against an externally persisted byte offset (clamp to `countLines(inbox)` + log the clamp) and stamps `(lines)` in the armed log, so the unit cannot be silently misread. Pure runtime, no DOM. **Board-staleness gate** (per policy #434 amendment, Delegate seq 105, msgId m-mptgrq23-104, commit 694cb20, 2026-05-31): at re-arm start, main (agentId === WS_PRIMARY_AGENT) compares **HEAD commit time vs state.json's last commit time** — `headCommitTime` (`git log -1 HEAD --format=%ct`) vs `stateLastCommitTime` (`git log -1 -- state.json --format=%ct`). When `headCommitTime > stateLastCommitTime`, HEAD has commits past the last state.json refresh → watcher exits with `wake("BOARD_STALE")`, forcing main to refresh the board before re-arming. When the two epochs are equal (state.json included in the HEAD commit), the gate passes. No wall-clock buffer is used: the board-update commit itself advances both HEAD and state.json together, so the gate naturally passes after a refresh — corrects a prior time-buffer version (now retired) that self-trapped because commit time always exceeded `state.json.updatedAt`. Mechanizes #410 (board real-time discipline) — converts the volitional "keep state.json fresh" rule into a mechanical re-arm gate. Workers exempt (they do not own state.json). See @machine derive `board_stale_gate`. (Distilled from constellation/reference/runtime/self-wake-watcher.sh — Constellation infinite-wait, AGENT-CONNECT §1.9.)
@expansion temperature=0.2 model=agent/claude template=estreux/v0.0.1
@targets vanilla
@profile supervisor
@source examples/ws-wait.sh(31-38) · examples/ws-wait.sh(46-55) · examples/ws-wait.sh(57-71) · examples/ws-wait.sh(73-92) · examples/ws-wait.sh(93-94)
# @source provenance per main upstream Delegate seq 159 (msgId m-mpu9febn-158, §F mapping, 2026-06-01).
# Range legend (repo-relative to examples/ws-wait.sh):
#   L31-38   : env defaults (INBOX / ICUR / FB / FCUR / WID / INTERVAL / MAX)
#   L46-55   : meaningful() filter (blocklist scan from cursor)
#   L57-71   : BOARD_STALE gate (§13.16.7 / #410 / #434 amendment) — probe L60-66 (headCommitTime + stateLastCommitTime via `git log -1 ... --format=%ct`), comparison L64-65 (headCommitTime > stateLastCommitTime), WAKE L67-70 (wake("BOARD_STALE") + exit)
#   L73-92   : poll loop (interval tick / inbox+feedback line read / meaningful gate / standby gate)
#   L93-94   : re-arm timeout (maxTicks exhausted → exit 0, agent re-arms next turn)
# (Pre-existing inline provenance in @intent — "Distilled from constellation/reference/runtime/self-wake-watcher.sh" — remains valid as narrative lineage; this @source directive promotes the BOARD_STALE gate to explicit line-precise lineage per eux-format-v1.md §3.8 and per §13.16.7 mechanization of #410 board real-time discipline.)
@state
inboxCursor    : number = 0        # processed **line count** for inbox (persisted to cursor file as a plain integer line count — never a byte offset; see @behavior arm() self-heal clamp and @machine derive `cursor_unit`)
feedbackCursor : number = 0        # processed-line count for feedback.jsonl
interval       : number = 5        # poll interval seconds (WS_WAIT_INTERVAL; "≤5s near-real-time")
maxTicks       : number = 588      # poll count before re-arm timeout (~49min = 5s×588)
tick           : number = 0        # current poll count
@ports
in   inbox        : string         # inbox path to watch (WS_INBOX; worker uses its own queue, not main's)
in   feedback     : string?        # feedback.jsonl path (WS_FEEDBACK). **Auto-derived from inbox** when not set: if `inbox` matches `<board>/_board/agents/<id>/inbox.jsonl`, derive `<board>/_board/feedback.jsonl`; otherwise stays null. Null after derivation = wake-trigger (1) feedback/standby is **dead** — user-submitted decisions/freeRequest will NOT wake the watcher. arm() emits a WARN in that case (see @behavior).
in   cursorFile   : string         # processed-cursor path (derived from inbox name if unset; per-queue, no collision)
in   agentId      : string         # my agentId (WS_AGENT_ID) — for armed log only
cmd  arm()        : (re)start the poll loop from current cursors — called on launch and after each wake-process cycle
out  wake(reason) : exit(0) on meaningful change — reason ∈ {action, feedback/standby, timeout-rearm}; exit = agent's next-turn trigger
deps clock        : sleep/timer    # injected poll timer (interval seconds)
deps fs           : file reader    # read inbox/feedback line counts + cursor files
deps stateRead    : function       # read state.json.standby (SSoT for standby on/off)
@behavior
arm              : **derive `feedback` from `inbox`** when not explicitly provided (board layout pattern `<board>/_board/agents/<id>/inbox.jsonl` → `<board>/_board/feedback.jsonl`); read inboxCursor (cursorFile) + feedbackCursor. **Self-heal cursor-unit drift**: if `inboxCursor > countLines(inbox)` (impossibly large for a line count — almost certainly a byte offset persisted by an external script, or a stale value from a truncated inbox), clamp `inboxCursor = countLines(inbox)`, re-persist, and log `cursor clamp <old>→<new> (byte-offset/stale 추정)`. Then log `armed(inbox, cursor=<N>(lines), agentId, interval, maxTicks, feedback)` — **explicitly stamp the unit `(lines)`** in the cursor field so any future operator sees the unit (a 5-second diagnosis instead of hours). If `feedback` is null after derivation, append `[WARN] feedback=null — board feedback events will NOT wake this watcher` on the same line (single log line, hard to miss). Enter poll loop. **Silent-disable principle**: any optional input that, when null, disables a wake-trigger MUST emit a WARN here, never silently.
pollTick         : every `interval`s — read inbox total lines (it), **feedback total (ft) only if `feedback` set, else 0** (the WARN was already surfaced in arm()), standby (sb). (1) **(feedback set AND ft>feedbackCursor)** OR sb!=true → wake("feedback/standby"). (2) it>inboxCursor → meaningful(inboxCursor)? wake("action") : absorb (inboxCursor=it, no wake). Else continue until maxTicks → re-arm timeout (exit 0, agent re-arms).
meaningful(from) : scan inbox lines from cursor; true if any line's name/type is NOT in the noise blocklist AND is in the meaningful allowlist. **Allowlist enumeration is sourced from Constellation §13.16.9 (Message classification by intent)** — the SSoT for board-directed vs A2A-intent name lists. The noise blocklist === §13.16.9 board-directed allowlist + transport-tier = {ServerNotice, AgentList, Status, ConnectionRestored, Heartbeat, Typing, UserPromptAccepted, PersistentAdapterSmoke, OnboardAck, WorkerInboxReceived, EditMessage, MainChanged, History, Ack, AckProcessed, AckCumulative, AckPolicyUpdate}. The meaningful allowlist === §13.16.9 A2A-intent allowlist = {Report, Delegate, WorkerReport, WorkerAck, AgentHello, Handoff, HandoffRequested, HandoffReady, Command, Priority, Cancel, UserPrompt, BlockerManifest, BlockerNudge, PRRequest, PRDraftReady, PRReviewAck, PRMergeRequest, PRMergeAck, PRStatusUpdate, DeadlockProbe, ReviewSLAAck, PreemptRequest, PreemptForce, MediationProposal, MediationAck, EscalationRequest}. Unknown names not in either list default to wake (fail-safe A2A-intent — silent-drop-of-A2A is the worse failure mode). **ev-agnostic, name-only** (per Constellation §13.16.6 v2.4.16 correction): the filter MUST NOT prepend a `grep '"ev":"inbound"'` stage. The `inbox.log` carries two envelope formats — legacy event-relay (`{"t":..., "ev":"inbound", "msg":{"name":...}}`) and direct inbound (`{"at":..., "name":..., "value":..., "source":"agent"}`); an ev-stage filters out the direct format entirely (it has no `ev` field) while the name blocklist already covers self-emission echo + transport noise regardless of which format the line carries. Diagnostic anchor: watchers `bv0u5h95p` + `bd7k7xoy3` (2026-06-01) REARM-timed-out despite live direct-format inbound because a v2.4.2-era ev-gate filtered all four meaningful lines before the name-stages saw them.
postWakeContract : the woken agent MUST process new entries, set inboxCursor = current total, then call arm() again. Skipping re-arm = monitoring stops (real incident: missed delegate). Confirm re-arm every turn before ending.
@machine
# reducer: (watchState, event) → watchState. The exit IS the wake signal for a turn-based runtime.
states: WATCHING(initial) · WOKEN · REARM · BOARD_STALE
dispatch by event:
  arm_start_board_stale : * → BOARD_STALE (guard: agentId === WS_PRIMARY_AGENT AND headCommitTime > stateLastCommitTime, where headCommitTime = `git log -1 HEAD --format=%ct` (current HEAD commit epoch seconds) and stateLastCommitTime = `git log -1 -- state.json --format=%ct` (state.json's last-commit epoch seconds); entry: wake("BOARD_STALE"), exit process — forces main to refresh state.json before re-arm. Workers exempt: they do not own state.json. See derive `board_stale_gate` + #434 amendment / Delegate seq 105 / msgId m-mptgrq23-104 / commit 694cb20 / 2026-05-31)
  meaningful_inbox : WATCHING → WOKEN    (guard: meaningful(cursor)=true; entry: wake("action"), exit process)
  noise_inbox      : WATCHING → WATCHING (guard: only blocklist names; entry: advance inboxCursor, no wake)
  feedback_or_standby_off : WATCHING → WOKEN (entry: wake("feedback/standby"), exit process)
  timeout          : WATCHING → REARM    (entry: log re-arm, exit 0 — agent re-arms next turn)
derive:
  routed         ← inbox is already a per-agent routed queue; no targetAgentId re-filter needed here
  rearm_duty     ← woken agent re-arms arm() after processing (infinite-wait invariant: never stop watching while joined)
  silent_disable ← any optional input that, when null, disables a wake-trigger MUST emit a WARN where it's resolved to null (see arm() WARN on feedback=null) — never silent. Symmetric to the watch-state invariant: an alive-but-deaf watcher is as bad as no watcher (a real incident: a downstream went dark for 4h because `WS_FEEDBACK` was missing and the armed log gave no signal).
  cursor_unit    ← `inboxCursor` is a **line count** (newline-delimited non-empty entries), persisted as a plain integer to `cursorFile`. The neighboring `local-bridge` runtime uses 'cursor' for a byte offset of its outbox — same word, different unit; arm() self-heals against an externally persisted byte offset (clamp to countLines + log) and stamps `(lines)` in the armed log, so the unit cannot be misread. A real incident: an operator persisted `statSync().size` to the watcher's cursor file (mental model "file cursor = byte position"), `countLines(69) > byteOffset(14543)` was permanently false → inbox-growth wake silently dead until manually `wc -l` corrected.
  board_stale_gate ← at re-arm start, main (agentId === WS_PRIMARY_AGENT) compares **two commit-time identities**: `headCommitTime` (`git log -1 HEAD --format=%ct` — epoch of current HEAD commit) vs `stateLastCommitTime` (`git log -1 -- state.json --format=%ct` — epoch of state.json's most recent commit). If `headCommitTime > stateLastCommitTime`, HEAD has commits past the last state.json refresh → watcher exits with `wake("BOARD_STALE")`, forcing main to refresh state.json before re-arm. When `headCommitTime === stateLastCommitTime` (state.json was included in the same HEAD commit), the gate passes — the board is current with HEAD. **Self-trap avoidance**: no wall-clock buffer is used because the board-update commit itself moves both HEAD and state.json forward together (their commit epochs become equal → gate naturally passes). The previous time-buffer version (`headEpoch − stateUpdatedAtEpoch > 120s` using `state.json.updatedAt`) self-trapped — since the act of updating the board is itself a commit, commit time always exceeds `state.json.updatedAt`, so any workflow + commit longer than the 120s buffer would never pass freshness even after a correct refresh. Comparing two commit identities (not wall-clock offsets) eliminates the trap: staleness only arises when commits land after the last state.json commit. **Workers exempt**: only main owns state.json; worker agents bypass this gate (the guard short-circuits when agentId !== WS_PRIMARY_AGENT). Mechanizes #410 (board real-time discipline) — converting the volitional "keep state.json fresh" rule into a hard machine gate where stale-board violations become a re-arm failure rather than a silent drift. Per policy #434 (amended); corrects the prior time-buffer version (now retired) per main upstream Delegate seq 105 / msgId m-mptgrq23-104 / commit 694cb20 / 2026-05-31.
